Project Overview and Goals:
 Powered by the active accretion of gas onto a super-massive black hole, quasars emit extreme luminosities, enabling them to be observed from great distances and providing powerful back-lights of the evolving matter distribution in the Universe across 12 Billion years. Absorption features observed in the spectra of distant quasars (quasar absorption lines; QALs) can sensitively trace the gas and dust in any foreground galaxies that intercept the line of sight to our telescopes (Figure 1).  Metal-enriched QALs probe the content and distribution of processed gas in and around galaxies as well as the geometry of large-scale outflows. However, due to the relative scarcity of bright quasars and the observational challenges of resolving faint foreground galaxies in close angular proximity to their sight lines, backlight studies have lacked the statistics required to produce a complete picture of the co-evolution of galaxies and their gaseous halos. This project aimed to address this long-standing problem using a combination of large spectroscopic quasar surveys like the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS), the new infrared capabilities of the Hubble Space Telescope (HST), and an increasing number of high-redshift galaxy surveys.

The major goals of this project, as stated in the approved proposal, were to:
 (I) extract the largest ever 3-&shy;D census of metal-rich absorbers from the SDSS-III quasar spectra;
 (II) analyze the properties and distribution of the extracted absorbers;
 (III) exploit deep galaxy surveys in regions of overlap with the SDSS quasar sample to reveal the    typical environments of metal absorbers at moderate and high redshift;
 (IV) employ detected QALs to constrain the physical distances to which galaxy and AGN outflows   extend as a function of galaxy properties and redshift;
 (V) create and distribute novel inquiry-based educational activities for science teachers and    students through the SDSS Skyserver website and the UW Space Place outreach center.
Outcomes and Findings:

I completed the construction of an automated pipeline for extracting metal absorption features from the SDSS-III quasar sample, which now contains &gt;250,000 unique spectra. I have produced a catalog of absorbers, which represents a 3-D map of enriched gas in the Universe from z~0.3 to z~4.  A catalog paper describing the absorber dataset is in preparation (Lundgren et al. in prep.), and these data have already contributed to multiple publications (Vikas et al. 2013; Lee et al. 2015? Perez-Rafols et al. 2015).

Directly studying the stellar properties of the galaxies that host these absorbers requires the sensitivity and resolution of HST.  In order to build a sample of absorber-galaxy pairs with maximum efficiency, I used the aforementioned absorption catalog to identify the most metal-rich quasar sight lines. I was was awarded an 18-&shy;orbit program to study these targets, which has produced the deepest ever imaging and redshift survey of galaxies hosting metal-rich absorbers. The observations of these quasar fields have provided the best available data to address the 3rd and 4th major goals of this project.  Initial results from this program were presented at the January 2015 American Astronomical Society Meeting (Seattle, WA) and the July 2015 Meeting on the Enrichment of Diffuse Gas in the Universe (Sexten Center for Astrophysics, Italy).  A paper describing the results is in preparation (Lundgren et al., in prep.).

Broader Impacts:

Throughout my fellowship term, I have been an active member of the SDSS Education and Public Outreach committee.  My contributions to the committee included producing educational materials designed to enable students and the public to discover the fundamentals of modern astronomy and to explore the SDSS database.  The activities to which I contributed were presented at the January 2014 Meeting of the American Astronomical Society (Washington, DC) and the August 2015...
